<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Thalli lanceolate when young, becoming somewhat ovate (rarely obovate) when mature; base cuneate, becoming umbilicate; 50-115 mm thick; males to at least 5.5 cm wide and more than 31 cm long; females to 12 cm wide and more than 28 cm long, but thalli mostly narrower; color uniform throughout the thallus except for reproductive areas, olive-green when fresh, drying to grayish or brownish purple. Thalli dioecious. Spermatangia in packets of 2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8. Mature zygotosporangia in packets of 2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4. Habitat: mid to high intertidal rock, usually associated with sand. Phenology: winter to early spring (a few thalli may persist as late as mid summer). Distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.Agardh" authorityYear="1899" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by unique 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">rbc</emphasis>
L and 18S rRNA gene sequences.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Saxicolous in the upper mid intertidal on rocks partially buried in sand at the south end of West Beach, Calvert Island, British Columbia, Canada (
<geoCoordinate degrees="51" direction="north" minutes="39.14" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="51.652332">51°39.14'N</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate degrees="128" direction="west" minutes="08.42" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="-128.14034">128°08.42'W</geoCoordinate>
), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">S.C. Lindstrom 15596</emphasis>
, 18 Feb 2014, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90636</emphasis>
. GenBank sequences KP903995, KP903996 (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">rbc</emphasis>
L), KP903910 (SSU).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="isotypes">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Isotypes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
SCL 15594 (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UC 2050591</emphasis>
), SCL 15599 (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90637</emphasis>
), SCL 15600 &amp; 15601 (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90638</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
This species is named for the biogeographic region in which it is found, using the terminology of 
<bibRefCitation author="Valentine, JW" journalOrPublisher="Limnology and Oceanography" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="198 - 211" publicationUrl="10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" refId="B35" refString="Valentine, JW, 1966. Numerical analysis of marine molluscan ranges on the extratropical northeastern Pacific shelf. Limnology and Oceanography 11: 198 - 211, DOI: 10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" title="Numerical analysis of marine molluscan ranges on the extratropical northeastern Pacific shelf." url="10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" volume="11" year="1966">Valentine (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, but with a modification of the boundaries to extend from Cape Mendocino, California, to the central coast of British Columbia. It also commemorates the centenary of the University of British Columbia herbarium, which was established in early 1916.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Calvert Island, British Columbia, Canada, to Cape Mendocino, California, USA.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. C. Lindstrom &amp; J. R. Hughey" authorityYear="2015" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia montereyensis" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="montereyensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia montereyensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. C. Lindstrom" authorityYear="2015" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia columbiensis" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="columbiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia columbiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are essentially morphologically identical and represent the southern and northern species of a vicariant pair, respectively.
</paragraph>
